Functional neuroimaging of traumatic brain injury: advances and clinical 
utility.

Irimia A(1), Van Horn JD(1).

Author information:
(1)USC Stevens Neuroimaging and Informatics Institute, Keck School of Medicine, 
University of Southern California, Los Angeles, CA, USA.

Functional deficits due to traumatic brain injury (TBI) can have significant and 
enduring consequences upon patients' life quality and expectancy. Although 
functional neuroimaging is essential for understanding TBI pathophysiology, an 
insufficient amount of effort has been dedicated to the task of translating 
functional neuroimaging findings into information with clinical utility. The 
purpose of this review is to summarize the use of functional neuroimaging 
techniques - especially functional magnetic resonance imaging, diffusion tensor 
imaging, positron emission tomography, magnetic resonance spectroscopy, and 
electroencephalography - for advancing current knowledge of TBI-related brain 
dysfunction and for improving the rehabilitation of TBI patients. We focus on 
seven core areas of functional deficits, namely consciousness, motor function, 
attention, memory, higher cognition, personality, and affect, and, for each of 
these, we summarize recent findings from neuroimaging studies which have 
provided substantial insight into brain function changes due to TBI. 
Recommendations are also provided to aid in setting the direction of future 
neuroimaging research and for understanding brain function changes after TBI.

